{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2775b4f1-5704-429e-bea5-86b0e4a4686b","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **`Window` lifecycle events**. You either subclass `Window` or subscribe to events in `CreateWindow`:\n\n**Option 1 – Custom Window subclass:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* was OnStart */ }\n    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* was OnSleep */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* was OnResume */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n```\n\n**Option 2 – Inline events in `CreateWindow`:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new MainPage());\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Mapping summary:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` / `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` / `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` / `Resumed` |\n\nMAUI also exposes `OnActivated` / `OnDeactivated` for finer-grained focus tracking, and platform-specific lifecycle hooks via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents()` in `MauiProgram.cs` if you need lower-level control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"258b8c91-8cc8-45c1-9730-382fd0a6500d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed significantly. The equivalent approach uses the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleEventHandler` pattern.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, `OnResume` virtual methods in the same way. \n\nInstead, you work with window lifecycle events—either by overriding `CreateWindow` and hooking into events like `Window.Created`, `Window.Resumed`, `Window.Stopped`, and `Window.Destroying`, or by subclassing `Window` and overriding methods like `OnCreated()`, `OnResumed()`, `OnStopped()`, and `OnDestroying()`.\n\nActually, I need to clarify this. The `Application` class in .NET MAUI doesn't expose `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` as overridable methods anymore—those were removed in favor of the `Window` class lifecycle approach, which is now the recommended pattern. The `Window` class provides the lifecycle events and methods you need instead.\n\nSo the mapping works like this: `Window.Created` replaces the old `OnStart`, `Window.Stopped` or `Deactivated` replaces `OnSleep`, and `Window.Resumed` replaces `OnResume`. You can implement this by subclassing `Window` and overriding those methods, subscribing to window events from your `Application`, or using platform-specific lifecycle configuration through `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in your `MauiProgram`.","outputTokens":1184,"requestId":"9429:20A32C:141F188:168B395:6A0670C0"},"id":"6d113cbf-62de-423b-be05-ae5502f6fed7","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:03:15.987Z","parentId":"00a4de76-e649-4365-8ab9-10452984aaa0"}
